ChatGPT said:

Short answer: a Custom GPT on its own cant do this end-to-end. It can read a job post and draft tailored CVs/letters, but it cannot reliably (or compliantly) 1) create accounts, 2) solve CAPTCHAs, 3) click through every ATS, or 4) submit forms across hundreds of sites. Youll need a small stack around the model.

Heres the fastest, 2-day path to something that actually works:

Whats feasible in 2 days (MVP)

Goal: Find matching roles, auto-draft CV + cover letter, auto-open the application page, auto-fill for a few common ATSes (e.g., Greenhouse/Lever/Workday), and log everything to Google Sheets. If a CAPTCHA or non-standard site appears, pause for you to complete manually.

Architecture (lean and proven)

  1. Job discovery

  • Sources: LinkedIn job alerts (email), Google Jobs alerts (email), a few company career pages you choose, and RSS/new-listing pages that are easy to parse.

  • Implementation options:

    • Easiest: set up email alerts parse your inbox for new job emails.

    • Also: scrape a small list of target company career pages (only those whose ToS allow it).

  1. JD parsing & matching

  • LLM extracts: required skills, nice-to-haves, responsibilities, screening questions.

  • Score match vs your skill profile; discard low matches.

  1. Tailored CV & cover letter

  • Keep a master resume JSON (skills, projects, bullets).

  • Use a DOCX/LaTeX template + Jinja2 to assemble a one-page CV variant and a cover letter for each job.

  • Export PDF.

  1. Application automation

  • Use Playwright (recommended) or Selenium to:

    • Open the job link.

    • If ATS is recognized (Greenhouse/Lever/Workday), fill standard fields, upload PDFs, answer simple yes/no/short text questions.

    • If login/account creation is required:

      • Attempt account creation only for pre-whitelisted domains youre comfortable with.

      • If CAPTCHA or multi-factor appears pause & notify you to complete, then resume autofill.

  • Do not try to bypass CAPTCHAsunreliable and often against ToS.

  1. Tracking

  • Log each job into Google Sheets: company, title, location, link, status, match score, date applied, notes.

  1. Notifications

  • Send you a summary (email/Slack/Discord): what was found, what was applied, what needs your attention.

Tools & components

  • LLM: any reliable API (for extracting requirements + writing CV/letters).

  • Browser automation: Playwright (Python or Node). Headless + stealth mode only when ToS permits basic automation; otherwise run headed and interact when prompted.

  • Docs: python-docx or LaTeX (xelatex) with Jinja2 templates export PDFs.

  • Storage: Google Sheets API for the tracker; local filesystem or cloud bucket for PDFs.

  • Email: Gmail API (read-only) to ingest job alerts and verify new account confirmation emails (when you choose to auto-create accounts).

  • Optional: n8n/Make/Zapier for glue (polling + triggering runs).

Concrete 2-day implementation plan

Day 1 (focus on value)

  1. Set up repos & creds

  • Create a small monorepo: /crawler, /llm, /apply, /templates, /tracker.

  • Enable Gmail API + Google Sheets API; save credentials.

  • Add a .env with your LLM API key and Google creds.

  1. Job intake (quick wins)

  • Parse Gmail job alerts (subject filters like Data Analyst, Machine Learning Engineer).

  • Also add 35 company career pages you care about (e.g., your dream employers). Keep it small for reliability.

  1. Matching & writing

  • Prompt the LLM to extract skills/requirements compute a simple cosine similarity vs your profile.

  • For matches above a threshold (say 0.7), render CV.pdf and CoverLetter.pdf from templates (Jinja2).

  1. Tracker

  • Create a Google Sheet with columns: Date, Company, Role, Location, Link, MatchScore, Status, Notes.

  • Write a helper to append rows.

Day 2 (controlled automation)

  1. Playwright flows

  • Implement Greenhouse and Lever autofill first (theyre common and fairly consistent):

    • Upload CV & cover letter.

    • Fill name, email, phone, location, work authorization, salary expectations if present (pull defaults from your profile JSON).

    • Answer yes/no questions when clearly safe (e.g., Do you require sponsorship?).

  • Implement a fallback:

    • If site not recognized or CAPTCHA appears open page and pause with a desktop notification; after you complete, script resumes to upload documents and hit submit (when possible).

  1. Account creation (opt-in)

  • For a small allowlist (e.g., Greenhouse SSO or a single employer portal you trust), try:

    • Registration form read Gmail for verification link click link continue.

  • If anything looks risky or blocked by ToS, the script stops and asks for manual action.

  1. End-to-end test

  • Run: ingest 510 postings generate documents try autofill on 23 Greenhouse/Lever links log to Sheet send summary.

Why a Custom GPT alone isnt enough

  • It cant run a real browser, manage sessions, upload files, or click arbitrary buttons across sites.

  • Most job portals deploy bot mitigations (device fingerprinting, rate limits, CAPTCHAs, CSRF tokens).

  • Terms of Service: many sites forbid full automation of submissions. Keep your system assistive, not fully autonomous everywhere.

Minimal code blueprint (you/your dev can paste and adapt)

Playwright (Python) Greenhouse/Lever autofill (skeleton)

python
from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright
import json, time, pathlib

PROFILE = json.load(open("profile.json"))
CV_PATH = pathlib.Path("out/CV.pdf").as_posix()
CL_PATH = pathlib.Path("out/CoverLetter.pdf").as_posix()

def fill_common_fields(page):
    def type_if(selector, value):
        if value and page.locator(selector).count():
            page.fill(selector, value)

    # common fields
    type_if('input[name="email"]', PROFILE["email"])
    type_if('input[name="name"]', f'{PROFILE["first_name"]} {PROFILE["last_name"]}')
    type_if('input[name="first_name"]', PROFILE["first_name"])
    type_if('input[name="last_name"]', PROFILE["last_name"])
    type_if('input[name="phone"]', PROFILE["phone"])
    type_if('input[name*="location"]', PROFILE["location"])
    # upload
    if page.locator('input[type="file"]').count():
        page.set_input_files('input[type="file"]', [CV_PATH, CL_PATH])

def apply_greenhouse(page):
    # heuristic selectors that work on most GH forms
    fill_common_fields(page)
    # yes/no questions
    for label in page.locator('label').all():
        text = label.inner_text().lower()
        if "sponsorship" in text:
            label.click()  # choose the first option; you can refine per your profile

def run(url):
    with sync_playwright() as p:
        browser = p.chromium.launch(headless=False)  # start headed to handle CAPTCHAs manually
        page = browser.new_page()
        page.goto(url, wait_until="domcontentloaded", timeout=60000)

        host = page.url.split("/")[2]
        if "greenhouse" in host:
            apply_greenhouse(page)
        elif "lever" in host:
            fill_common_fields(page)
        else:
            print("Unrecognized ATS  manual step recommended.")
        time.sleep(2)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    run("https://boards.greenhouse.io/example/jobs/12345")

Google Sheets logger (Python)

python
from googleapiclient.discovery import build
from google.oauth2.service_account import Credentials
from datetime import datetime

def log_to_sheet(sheet_id, row):
    creds = Credentials.from_service_account_file("service_account.json", scopes=[
        "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets"
    ])
    svc = build('sheets', 'v4', credentials=creds)
    body = {"values": [row]}
    svc.spreadsheets().values().append(
        spreadsheetId=sheet_id,
        range="Applications!A:Z",
        valueInputOption="USER_ENTERED",
        body=body
    ).execute()

# example
log_to_sheet("YOUR_SHEET_ID", [
    datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d"),
    "Acme", "Data Analyst", "Remote", "https://...", 0.82, "Applied", "Auto-filled GH"
])

2) LLM prompt: parse job description & compute match

Use this to extract role details and a match score.

python
SYSTEM: You are a strict extractor. Return ONLY JSON.

USER: Here is a job posting: """<paste full job description>"""

TASK: Extract:
- title
- company
- location
- required_skills (list)
- preferred_skills (list)
- responsibilities (short list)
- screening_questions (if any)
Then compare the 'required_skills' to this candidate profile (provide profile skills list) and compute a match_score from 0.0 to 1.0 (simple: matches/required_count). Output JSON with these keys.

Example output (LLM JSON) helps you decide thresholds (e.g., only proceed if match_score >= 0.65).

3) LLM prompt: generate ATS-friendly tailored CV bullets

This prompt creates a short 1-page CV tailored to JD keywords.

vbnet
SYSTEM: Output a concise one-page CV in JSON with sections: header, summary, skills, experience (max 6 bullets per role), projects, education. Use the job_title, required_skills, and responsibilities to prioritize and rewrite bullets from the master profile to match keywords and be ATS-friendly.

USER: Candidate profile: <profile.json content>
Job info: <parsed JD JSON>

INSTRUCTIONS:
- Keep the CV to one page.
- Reorder bullets so the most relevant skills appear first.
- Emphasize exact keywords from required_skills.
- Format bullets as short accomplishments, include metrics when possible.
Return only JSON.

Then render that JSON into a DOCX template (python-docx or docxtpl) and export to PDF.

6) Playwright skeleton to open and autofill (simple)

This opens a job page and tries to fill common fields. Save as apply.py. Run headed (not fully headless) so you can intervene for CAPTCHAs.

python
from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright
import json, time

PROFILE = json.load(open("profile.json"))

def fill_common(page):
    def try_fill(selector, value):
        try:
            if page.locator(selector).count() and value:
                page.fill(selector, value)
        except:
            pass

    try_fill('input[name="email"]', PROFILE["email"])
    try_fill('input[name="first_name"]', PROFILE["first_name"])
    try_fill('input[name="last_name"]', PROFILE["last_name"])
    try_fill('input[name="phone"]', PROFILE["phone"])
    # Upload any file inputs
    if page.locator('input[type="file"]').count():
        page.set_input_files('input[type="file"]', ["./out/CV.pdf"])

def apply_url(url):
    with sync_playwright() as p:
        browser = p.chromium.launch(headless=False)
        page = browser.new_page()
        page.goto(url, wait_until='domcontentloaded', timeout=60000)
        fill_common(page)
        # leave for manual confirmation
        print("Open in browser. Complete captcha / custom fields manually if needed.")
        time.sleep(3)
        # optionally click submit if a clear button is found
        # page.click('button[type="submit"]')
        browser.close()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    apply_url("https://example-job-link")

Important: do not bypass CAPTCHAs / MFA. Use automation only for convenience and in compliance with the sites terms.

3 JD Match CV prompt (Step 3)

python
SYSTEM: You are a structured job analyzer.

USER: Here is a job posting:
"""
{{JOB_DESCRIPTION}}
"""

Candidate profile:
{{PROFILE_JSON}}

TASKS:
1. Extract and return in JSON:
   - title
   - company
   - location
   - required_skills (list)
   - preferred_skills (list)
   - key_responsibilities (list)

{

  "company": "",
  "location": "",
  "required_skills": [],
  "preferred_skills": [],
  "key_responsibilities": [],

  "comment": ""
}

Youll copy-paste this prompt into ChatGPT (or use via API later).
Replace {{JOB_DESCRIPTION}} with the job post text and {{PROFILE_JSON}} with your profile.json content.

This gives you a structured result and match score.

STEP 1 Make a new file

In VS Code:

STEP 2 Copy this code inside it

Click inside the new file and paste this code 

python
import openai
import json

# Load your profile
with open("../profile.json", "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    profile = json.load(f)

# Paste your latest job match JSON here (the one GPT gave you)
job_data = {
    "title": "ML Engineer",
    "company": "",
    "location": "Norway",
    "required_skills": [
        "Python (2+ years)",
        "SQL (2+ years)",
        "Experience with engineering data",
        "Practical experience with language models"
    ],
    "preferred_skills": [
        "Deploying production-grade ML",
        "Collaboration with data scientists",
        "Curiosity and willingness to learn"
    ],
    "key_responsibilities": [
        "Explore, develop, and productionize ML solutions",
        "Ensure models are robust, scalable, and valuable",
        "Collaborate with data and software teams"
    ],
    "match_score": 0.5,
    "comment": "Strong fit on Python and SQL; missing IoT and LLM-specific experience."
}

# -------------- CONFIG ----------------
# Replace this with your OpenAI API key (get from https://platform.openai.com)
openai.api_key = "YOUR_API_KEY_HERE"
# -------------------------------------

#  Generate tailored CV
cv_prompt = f"""
You are an expert resume writer.

Based on this candidate profile:
{json.dumps(profile, indent=2)}

And this job:
{json.dumps(job_data, indent=2)}

Write a short, one-page text CV (plain text, no formatting) that highlights the candidate's strengths relevant to the job, 
and uses the same keywords from the job description.
Keep it under 300 words.
"""

cv_response = openai.ChatCompletion.create(
    model="gpt-4o-mini",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": cv_prompt}]
)

cv_text = cv_response.choices[0].message.content.strip()

#  Generate cover letter
cl_prompt = f"""
Write a short cover letter for this job.
Mention the company name if given, otherwise just 'your organization'.
Keep it 3 paragraphs, professional but friendly.
Focus on how the candidate fits the role and is eager to contribute.
Use information from:
Profile:
{json.dumps(profile, indent=2)}
Job:
{json.dumps(job_data, indent=2)}
"""

cl_response = openai.ChatCompletion.create(
    model="gpt-4o-mini",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": cl_prompt}]
)

cl_text = cl_response.choices[0].message.content.strip()

# Save outputs
with open("../out/cv_output.txt", "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    f.write(cv_text)

with open("../out/cover_letter.txt", "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    f.write(cl_text)

print(" Done! Check the 'out' folder for cv_output.txt and cover_letter.txt.")

from googleapiclient.discovery import build
from google.oauth2.service_account import Credentials
from datetime import datetime

def log_to_sheet(sheet_id, row):
    creds = Credentials.from_service_account_file("../service_account.json", scopes=[
        "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets"
    ])
    service = build('sheets', 'v4', credentials=creds)
    body = {"values": [row]}
    service.spreadsheets().values().append(
        spreadsheetId=sheet_id,
        range="Sheet1!A:G",
        valueInputOption="USER_ENTERED",
        body=body
    ).execute()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    #  replace this with your Sheet ID (look at the link after /d/)

        "https://example.com",
        0.85,
        "Applied",
        "Auto-filled via script"
    ])

import openai
import json
from datetime import datetime

# Load your profile (for contact info only)
with open("../profile.json", "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    profile = json.load(f)

#  Replace with your OpenAI API key
openai.api_key = "YOUR_API_KEY_HERE"

# ---- Job description to tailor for ----
job_description = """
Paste the job description text here...
"""

# ---- Prompt ----
prompt = f"""
You are an expert recruiter assistant.

Write a short, professional cover letter for the job below,
using the candidate's real CV as-is (do NOT invent new skills, education, or projects).
Only reference information already present in the candidate profile.
Keep it 3 short paragraphs, friendly but formal.

Candidate:
{json.dumps(profile, indent=2)}

Job:
{job_description}
"""

response = openai.ChatCompletion.create(
    model="gpt-4o-mini",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": prompt}]
)

cover_letter = response.choices[0].message.content.strip()

# Save to file
filename = f"../out/cover_letter_{datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d_%H%M%S')}.txt"
with open(filename, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    f.write(cover_letter)

print(" Cover letter created:", filename)
print(" Remember to attach CV_Main.pdf with this letter when applying.")

3) create the detector script

in VS Code left panel, right-click scripts New File name it:

fetch_jobs_from_gmail.py

paste this code (dont worry, Ill explain right after):

python
import os, re, json, base64, datetime
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
from google.oauth2.credentials import Credentials
from google_auth_oauthlib.flow import InstalledAppFlow
from googleapiclient.discovery import build

# ---- settings you can tweak ----
SAVE_DIR = "../jobs"                    # where we save found jobs
LABEL_QUERY = 'in:inbox newer_than:7d'  # search emails from last 7 days
SENDERS = [
    "jobs-noreply@linkedin.com",        # LinkedIn alerts
    "no-reply@linkedin.com",
    "alerts-noreply@google.com",        # Google Jobs alerts
]
ROLE_KEYWORDS = [
    "data analyst", "data scientist", "ml engineer", "machine learning",
    "junior data scientist", "junior data analyst"
]
# --------------------------------

SCOPES = ["https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly"]

def get_service():
    # token.json stores the user's access/refresh tokens
    creds = None
    if os.path.exists("../token.json"):
        creds = Credentials.from_authorized_user_file("../token.json", SCOPES)
    if not creds or not creds.valid:
        if creds and creds.expired and creds.refresh_token:
            from google.auth.transport.requests import Request
            creds.refresh(Request())
        else:
            flow = InstalledAppFlow.from_client_secrets_file("../client_secret.json", SCOPES)
            creds = flow.run_local_server(port=0)
        with open("../token.json", "w") as token:
            token.write(creds.to_json())
    return build("gmail", "v1", credentials=creds)

def clean_filename(s: str) -> str:
    s = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z0-9._-]+", "_", s.strip())
    return s[:120]

def extract_urls_from_html(html: str):
    soup = BeautifulSoup(html, "lxml")
    urls = set()
    for a in soup.find_all("a", href=True):
        href = a["href"]
        if href.startswith("http"):
            urls.add(href)
    return list(urls)

def looks_like_job(title_or_text: str) -> bool:
    low = title_or_text.lower()
    return any(k in low for k in ROLE_KEYWORDS)

def main():
    service = get_service()
    query = LABEL_QUERY
    # apply sender filters to reduce noise
    sender_part = " OR ".join([f'from:{s}' for s in SENDERS])
    if sender_part:
        query = f"({query}) ({sender_part})"

    results = service.users().messages().list(userId="me", q=query, maxResults=25).execute()
    messages = results.get("messages", [])
    if not messages:
        print("No recent job emails found.")
        return

    os.makedirs(SAVE_DIR, exist_ok=True)
    saved_count = 0

    for m in messages:
        msg = service.users().messages().get(userId="me", id=m["id"], format="full").execute()
        headers = msg["payload"].get("headers", [])
        subject = next((h["value"] for h in headers if h["name"].lower()=="subject"), "(no subject)")
        frm = next((h["value"] for h in headers if h["name"].lower()=="from"), "")
        date = next((h["value"] for h in headers if h["name"].lower()=="date"), "")
        # find HTML part
        parts = msg["payload"].get("parts", [])
        html_body = ""
        def walk(parts):
            nonlocal html_body
            for p in parts:
                if p.get("mimeType") == "text/html":
                    data = p["body"].get("data")
                    if data:
                        html_body = base64.urlsafe_b64decode(data).decode("utf-8", errors="ignore")
                elif p.get("parts"):
                    walk(p["parts"])
        if parts:
            walk(parts)
        else:
            # sometimes body is right at payload.body
            data = msg["payload"]["body"].get("data")
            if data:
                html_body = base64.urlsafe_b64decode(data).decode("utf-8", errors="ignore")

        if not html_body:
            continue

        urls = extract_urls_from_html(html_body)

        # keep only URLs that look like jobs or from known job domains
        JOB_DOMAINS = ["linkedin.com", "greenhouse.io", "lever.co", "workday", "smartrecruiters", "jobs", "careers"]
        job_urls = [u for u in urls if any(d in u.lower() for d in JOB_DOMAINS)]

        # save a small job "inbox" file for each email
        if job_urls and (looks_like_job(subject) or looks_like_job(html_body)):
            ts = datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M%S")
            base = clean_filename(subject) or "job_alert"
            path = os.path.join(SAVE_DIR, f"{ts}__{base}.txt")
            with open(path, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                f.write(f"Subject: {subject}\nFrom: {frm}\nDate: {date}\n\nLinks:\n")
                for u in job_urls:
                    f.write(u + "\n")
            print(" saved job links to:", path)
            saved_count += 1

    print(f" Done. Saved {saved_count} job link files into {SAVE_DIR}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

5) (optional) fetch job page text for analysis

if you want the full job description text (to feed the analyzer automatically), we can safely fetch pages only from an allowlist of common ATS sites (e.g., greenhouse, lever). well skip anything else.

create a file scripts/fetch_job_pages.py:

python
import os, re, time, requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

JOBS_DIR = "../jobs"
OUT_DIR = "../jobs/fetched"
ALLOW_DOMAINS = ["greenhouse.io", "lever.co"]

os.makedirs(OUT_DIR, exist_ok=True)

def domain_ok(url):
    low = url.lower()
    return any(d in low for d in ALLOW_DOMAINS)

def extract_text(url):
    r = requests.get(url, timeout=15, headers={"User-Agent":"Mozilla/5.0"})
    r.raise_for_status()
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, "lxml")
    # crude: pull main text content
    for tag in soup(["script","style","nav","footer","header"]):
        tag.decompose()
    text = " ".join(soup.get_text("\n").split())
    return text[:50000]  # cap length

def main():
    for name in os.listdir(JOBS_DIR):
        if not name.endswith(".txt"):
            continue
        path = os.path.join(JOBS_DIR, name)
        with open(path, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
            lines = f.read().splitlines()
        links = [ln for ln in lines if ln.startswith("http")]
        links = [u for u in links if domain_ok(u)]
        if not links:
            continue
        out_name = name.replace(".txt", ".jd.txt")
        out_path = os.path.join(OUT_DIR, out_name)
        if os.path.exists(out_path):
            continue
        all_texts = []
        for u in links[:3]:  # try first few
            try:
                txt = extract_text(u)
                all_texts.append(f"URL: {u}\n\n{txt}\n\n" + "-"*60 + "\n")
                time.sleep(1)
            except Exception as e:
                print("skip", u, e)
        if all_texts:
            with open(out_path, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                f.write("\n".join(all_texts))
            print(" saved JD text:", out_path)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

install requests if needed:

pip install requests

we kept this ethical: only allowed common ATS domains; no aggressive crawling; just a couple URLs per email.
